nt-weight:bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 47\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 104\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 77\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 181\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 50.5\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 33.0\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 1\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 3\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 3.0\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 0\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 5\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 0\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 0\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 0\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 7\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nMiller was projected to be a second round pick in the [[2010 NFL Draft]] had he passed on his senior season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/sports/college/texasam/7310876.html |title=A&M can be thankful it's still Miller time: LB passed up NFL for senior year with Aggies |first=Brent |last=Zwerneman |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=November 24, 2010 }}</ref> He entered the [[2011 NFL Draft]] regarded as one of the best 3\u20134 outside linebackers available by NFL draft experts and scouts and was projected to be a top five draft pick.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Tony |last=Pauline |title=Bruce Carter, Akeem Ayers headline list of top-10 draft-eligible linebackers |work=Sports Illustrated |date=December 13, 2010 |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/football/nfl/12/13/draft.linebackers/ }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft |title=NFL Draft 2011 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=March 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/feed/2010-09/draft-dish/story/mock-draft-luck-would-re-energize-panthers-listless-offense |title=Mock Draft: Luck would re-energize Panthers' listless offense |work=Sporting News |first=Russ |last=Lande |date=December 23, 2010 |access-date=December 23, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224015613/http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/feed/2010-09/draft-dish/story/mock-draft-luck-would-re-energize-panthers-listless-offense |archive-date=December 24, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/nfl/draft2011/insider/news/story?page=KiperMockDraft3.0 |title=2011 NFL Mock Draft 3.0 |work=ESPN.com |date=March 9, 2011 |first=Mel |last=Kiper }}</ref> At the 2011 [[Senior Bowl]], Miller was the Defensive MVP.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.profootballweekly.com/2011/02/05/miller-at-no-3-makes-sense-for-bills |title=Miller at No. 3 makes sense for Bills |magazine=Pro Football Weekly |date=February 5, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210125459/http://www.profootballweekly.com/2011/02/05/miller-at-no-3-makes-sense-for-bills |archive-date=February 10, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Among linebackers at the 2011 NFL Combine, Miller ranked 2nd in the 40-yard dash, 3rd in the vertical jump, 1st in the broad jump, 3rd in the 20-yard shuttle, T-1st in the 3-cone drill, and 1st in the 60-yard shuttle. His 11.15-second 60-yard shuttle broke the combine linebacker record. At the Texas A&M Pro Day in March 2011, Miller ran a 4.49 40-yard dash.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Von-Miller-runs-a-449.html |title=Von Miller runs a 4.49 |publisher=National Football Post |date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311140237/http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Von-Miller-runs-a-449.html |archive-date=March 11, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 2\u215d\n|       weight = 246\n|         dash = 4.53\n|    ten split = 1.62\n| twenty split = 2.64\n|      shuttle = 4.06\n|   cone drill = 6.70\n|     vertical = 37\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 6\n|        bench = 21\n|    wonderlic = N/A\n|     arm span = 33\u00bd\n|    hand span = 9\u00bc\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/thehuddle/post/2011/02/olb-von-miller-justifying-nfl-draft-stock-with-strong-combine/1 |title=OLB Von Miller justifying NFL draft stock with strong combine |newspaper=USA Today |date=February 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2011 |first=Nate |last=Davis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nfl.com/2011/02/28/von-miller-cements-his-top-billing/ |title=Von Miller cements his top billing |publisher=NFL.com Blogs |date=February 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2011}}</ref>\n}} \n\nIn March 2011, Miller was selected to represent top flight rookies in the NFL Labor Union talks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williamson |first=Bill |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/25308/will-von-miller-be-blackballed |title=Will Von Miller be blackballed? |publisher=ESPN, AFC West Blog |date= |accessdate=March 18, 2011}}</ref> He was persuaded by former NFL running back [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] to join the lawsuit.<ref name=SIapr2011/>\n\nDuring the Texas A&M Pro Day, however, one scout compared him to Hall of Famer [[Derrick Thomas]], while Bengals defensive coordinator [[Mike Zimmer]] compared him to Cardinals linebacker [[Joey Porter]].<ref name=ST309>{{cite news|last=Williams |first=Charean |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/2011/03/09/2909722/texas-am-product-von-miller-continues.html |title=Texas A&M product Von Miller continues to impress NFL scouts |newspaper=Fort Worth Star Telegram |date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=March 18, 2011}}</ref> [[NFL Network]] Analyst [[Mike Mayock]], who rated Miller as the second-best player in the draft, stated that Miller reminds him of a smaller version of [[DeMarcus Ware]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/story/09000d5d81eb70a5/article/defensive-line-leads-the-way-on-list-of-top-32-prospects |title=news: Defensive players lead the way on list of top 32 prospects |website=NFL.com |accessdate=March 18, 2011}}</ref> Miller's then-personal trainer, Dan Brandenburg, who also worked with first round picks [[Clay Matthews III]] and [[Sean Weatherspoon]], stated Miller is the best athlete of all three.<ref name=SIapr2011/>\n\n===Denver Broncos===\n[[File:Von Miller (2011).jpg|thumb|Miller in 2011]]\n[[File:Von Miller signing autographs at Transit Center Manas-March 2013.jpg|thumb|right|Miller signing autographs for U.S. troops at [[Transit Center at Manas]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], in March 2013]]\nMiller was drafted by the [[Denver Broncos]] second overall in the [[2011 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/draft.htm |title=2011 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> He was the highest selected linebacker since [[LaVar Arrington]] went No. 2 to the [[Washington Redskins]] in [[2000 NFL Draft|2000]]. He also became the Aggies' highest draft pick since [[Quentin Coryatt]], who was selected second overall in [[1992 NFL Draft|1992]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/sports/college/texasam/7454303.html |title=Hurdling serves Miller well: Star survives many pitfalls by clearing obstacles |first=Brent |last=Zwerneman |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=March 2, 2011 }}</ref> The selection of Miller surprised certain experts. Denver was switching from a [[3\u20134 defense]] to a [[4\u20133 defense|4\u20133]], a defense which seemed counter-intuitive to Miller's strengths. Former Broncos quarterback [[John Elway]], who is also the executive vice president of the franchise, said Miller is \"a type of guy that comes around every 10 years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nflnation/post/_/id/40289/john-elway-suddenly-likes-no-58|title=John Elway suddenly likes No. 58|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, 2011, Miller officially signed with the Denver Broncos. He wears No. 58 in honor of his favorite football player, the late former [[Kansas City Chiefs]] Hall of Fame linebacker [[Derrick Thomas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/31756/rookie-lb-centerpiece-of-elways-broncos|title=Rookie LB centerpiece of Elway's Broncos|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\nOn September 12, 2011, in his first career play from scrimmage, Miller forced a fumble against the [[2011 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109120den.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Denver Broncos - September 12th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> On September 18, 2011, he had his first sack on [[Andy Dalton (American football)|Andy Dalton]] when the Broncos played the [[2011 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_18926225 | work=Denver Post | title=Broncos' McGahee rushes for 101 yards against Bengals | date=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nMiller was named the AFC Defensive Player of the Week for his Week 11 performance against the [[2011 New York Jets season|New York Jets]].<ref>[http://aol.sportingnews.com/nfl/story/2011-11-23/denver-broncos-team-report-team-pleased-with-von-millers-development Sportingnews.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127212408/http://aol.sportingnews.com/nfl/story/2011-11-23/denver-broncos-team-report-team-pleased-with-von-millers-development |date=November 27, 2011 }}</ref> The Broncos made the playoffs and faced off against the [[2011 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in the [[2011\u201312_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Denver_Broncos_29,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_23_(OT)|Wild Card Round]]. In his playoff debut, Miller had three solo tackles and one quarterback hit in the 29\u201323 overtime victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201080den.htm |title=Wild Card - Pittsburgh Steelers at Denver Broncos - January 8th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2011\u201312_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_New_England_Patriots_45,_Denver_Broncos_10|Divisional Round]] against the [[2011 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], he had two quarterback hits in the 45-10 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201140nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Denver Broncos at New England Patriots - January 14th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMiller was selected to the [[2012 Pro Bowl]]<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_19626869 | work=Denver Post | first=Lindsay H. | last=Jones | title=Broncos Bailey, Miller, Dumervil make NFL Pro Bowl roster; Tebow an alternate | date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> and was named AP Defensive Rookie of the Year.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190103005156/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/broncos-lb-von-miller-wins-2011-ap-defensive-rookie-of-year/2012/02/04/gIQADPvDqQ_story.html The Washington Post] </ref> Overall, in 907 snaps, he recorded 11.5 sacks, 19 quarterback hits and 29 quarterback hurries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/blogs/sports/2012-06-16/the-nfl-beat-awards-shower/|title='The NFL Beat': Awards Shower|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> He was fined three times during \nseason.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcwest/post/_/id/39017/von-millers-fine-total-rises|title=Von Miller's fine total rises|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2012 season====\nMiller got off to a quick start in his second season, registering 10 sacks in nine games. In this period, he recorded 30 quarterback hurries, more than he had during his entire 2011 campaign. Thanks to this tremendous start, he was considered an MVP candidate. On November 16, he was fined $21,000 for a hit on [[2012 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] quarterback [[Cam Newton]] in Week 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000095952/article/fines-roundup-tim-dobbins-of-texans-fined-for-jay-cutler-hit|title=Fines roundup: Tim Dobbins of Texans fined for Jay Cutler hit|work=[[National Football League]]|date=November 16, 2012|accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref> He received his second career AFC Defensive Player of the Week honor after recording three sacks and two forced fumbles against the [[2012 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]] the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/11/21/von-miller-wins-afc-defensive-player-of-the-week-honors/|title=Von Miller wins AFC defensive player of the week honors - ProFootballTalk|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> For his efforts during the month of November, he was awarded AFC Defensive Player of the Month. On December 26, 2012, he was announced the starting Outside Linebacker in the AFC division for the [[2013 Pro Bowl]].<ref>[http://blog.denverbroncos.com/denverbroncos/miller-earns-afc-defensive-player-of-the-month/ Denverbroncos.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202112252/http://blog.denverbroncos.com/denverbroncos/miller-earns-afc-defensive-player-of-the-month/ |date=December 2, 2012 }}</ref> Miller finished the season third in sacks with eighteen and a half, breaking a Denver Broncos record of seventeen previously held by [[Elvis Dumervil]]. He also capped off the 2012 season finishing second in voting for Defensive Player of the Year and being named first-team All-Pro.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/allpro.htm |title=2012 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2012\u201313_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Baltimore_Ravens_38,_Denver_Broncos_35_(2OT)|Divisional Round]] of the playoffs, Miller had nine total tackles and two quarterback hits in the 38\u201335 2OT loss to the [[2012 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201301120den.htm |title=Divisional Round - Baltimore Ravens at Denver Broncos - January 12th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Miller teamed up with [[Ubisoft]], makers of the video game ''[[The Hip Hop Dance Experience]]'', to create his very own sack celebration dance called \"The DeSoto Shuffle\" that was inspired by the video game.  Each time he performed the dance during a game, Ubisoft made a charitable donation to Von's Vision, a foundation devoted to providing eye care and glasses to underprivileged youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/blog/eye-on-football/20551601/hiphop-experience-mercifully-helping-von-miller-reinvent-his-sack-dance|title='Hip-Hop Experience' mercifully helping Von Miller reinvent his sack dance|work=CBSSports.com|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:U.S. Army Maj. Gen. Robert Abrams the commanding officer of Regional Command-South and Third Infantry Division, and Command Sgt. Maj. Edd Watson, Third Infantry Division and Regional Command-South senior 130319-A-VM825-497.jpg|thumb|left|Miller (third from right) was one of several NFL players who visited US Army soldiers in Afghanistan during the 2013 offseason.]]\n\n====2013 season====\nPrior to the 2013 season, [[NFL Network]] listed Miller as the 9th-ranked player in its [[NFL: The Top 100 Players of 2013]] program, which is voted on by players in the NFL.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.nfl.com/top100/2013#video=0ap2000000214421 |title=Top 100 Players of 2013 |website=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, ESPN reported that Miller had been suspended four games for violating league policy, pending appeal. He [[tweeted]] that he did \"nothing wrong\". In August 2013, he lost the appeal and was suspended for six games. The six-game suspension arose after the NFL learned that he attempted to cheat a drug test. He became eligible to play on October 20, 2013, when the Broncos played the [[2013 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/broncos/2013/09/22/von-miller-urine-sample-conspiracy/2849821/|title=Broncos' Von Miller tried to swap out urine sample | work=USA Today | first1=Lindsay H.|last1=Jones|date=September 22, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9707976/von-miller-denver-broncos-urine-collector-tried-cheat-test |title=Von Miller of Denver Broncos, urine collector tried to cheat test |website=Espn.go.com |date=September 22, 2013 |accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> On November 24, in a loss to the [[2013 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], he recovered a [[Stevan Ridley]] fumble and took it 60 yards for a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201311240nwe.htm |title=Denver Broncos at New England Patriots - November 24th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> It was the second touchdown of his career. He did fairly well upon his return, but his season was ended prematurely when he [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|tore his ACL]] on December 22, 2013 during a win on the road at the [[2013 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]]. Without Miller, the Broncos reached [[Super Bowl XLVIII]], but lost 43\u20138 to the [[2013 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Jones |first=Ross |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/von-miller-suffers-dreaded-torn-acl-122313 |title=Von Miller suffers dreaded torn ACL &#124; FOX Sports |website=Msn.foxsports.com |date=December 23, 2013 |accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\nAfter recovering from his ACL injury, Miller looked to improve his play in his fourth season with the Broncos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/hochman/ci_26669658/broncos-von-miller-is-back-and-thats-bad?source=rss|title=Hochman: Broncos' Von Miller is back, and that's bad news for opponents|author=Benjamin Hochman The Denver Post|date=October 6, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> He did so with 14 sacks, 59 tackles, and a forced fumble.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MillVo00.htm |title=Von Miller 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2014\u201315_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Indianapolis_Colts_24,_Denver_Broncos_13|Divisional Round]] of the playoffs against the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had six total tackles and one quarterback hit in the 24\u201313 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501110den.htm |title=Divisional Round - Indianapolis Colts at Denver Broncos - January 11th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n[[File:Von Miller Super Bowl 50.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Miller in [[Super Bowl 50]]]]\nOn September 17, 2015, Miller became the third-fastest player in NFL history to reach 50 sacks career (58 games). The only ones to get there faster than him were [[Reggie White]] (40 games) and [[Derrick Thomas]] (54).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://den.247sports.com/Bolt/Von-Miller-third-fastest-to-50-sacks-in-NFL-history-39505606 |title=NFL - Von Miller third-fastest to 50 sacks in NFL history |website=247sports.com |url-status=dead |access-date=September 18, 2015}}</ref> Overall, in the 2015 season, Miller finished with 11 sacks, 35 total tackles, 32 quarterback hits, one pass defensed, and four forced fumbles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MillVo00.htm |title=Von Miller 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015\u201316_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Denver_Broncos_23,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_16|Divisional Round]] against the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], he had two total tackles in the 23\u201316 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601170den.htm |title=Divisional Round - Pittsburgh Steelers at Denver Broncos - January 17th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> During the [[2015\u201316_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Denver_Broncos_20,_New_England_Patriots_18|AFC Championship]] against the [[2015 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Miller sacked [[Tom Brady]] 2.5 times, breaking a Broncos single-game playoff record and also had an interception in the second quarter of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000627738/article/von-miller-makes-life-hell-for-tom-brady|title=Broncos LB Von Miller makes life hell for Tom Brady|work=NFL.com|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Super Bowl 50]], facing the heavily favored [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] who held the top-ranked offense, the Broncos won 24\u201310. In the first quarter, on a 3rd-and-10 from the 15-yard line, Miller knocked the ball out of Panthers quarterback [[Cam Newton]]'s hands while sacking him, and defensive end [[Malik Jackson (defensive end)|Malik Jackson]] recovered it in the end zone for a Broncos touchdown, giving the team a 10\u20130 lead. This was the first fumble return touchdown in a Super Bowl since [[Super Bowl XXVIII]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/02/07/us/super-bowl-50-gameday/ |title=Super Bowl 2016: Broncos' defense dominates as Peyton Manning wins second title |last=Martin |first=Jill |date=February 8, 2016 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> With 4:51 left in regulation and the Broncos leading 16\u201310, Miller forced a second fumble from Newton to end the Panthers' potential game-winning drive, and the Broncos offense afterwards scored a touchdown to seal the victory. Miller recorded six tackles, 2.5 sacks, two forced fumbles, and two quarterback hurries, and was named [[Super Bowl MVP]] for his performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/02/07/von-miller-wins-super-bowl-50-mvp/|title=Von Miller wins Super Bowl 50 MVP|last=Alper|first=Josh|date=February 7, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMiller was named to his fourth Pro Bowl, earned his second First-team All-Pro, and was ranked 15th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000671922/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-15-Von-Miller|title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 15 Von Miller|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nOn March 1, 2016, the Broncos placed the exclusive [[franchise tag]] on Miller.<ref>{{cite web|work=NFL.com|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000640432/article/von-miller-franchise-tagged-by-denver-broncos|title=Von Miller franchise tagged by Denver Broncos|first=Gregg|last=Rosenthal|date=March 1, 2016|accessdate=March 12, 2016}}</ref> On July 15, Miller signed a 6-year deal worth $114.5 million featuring $70 million guaranteed with the Broncos. He became the highest paid defensive player in NFL history, with the highest amount of guaranteed salary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000674882/article/von-miller-strikes-new-longterm-deal-with-broncos |title=Von Miller, Broncos agree on six-year, $114.5M deal |first=Connor|last=Orr|website=NFL.com|date=July 15, 2016|accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/broncos/2016/07/14/von-miller-denver-broncos-contract-negotiations-update/87109742/ |title=Von Miller expected to accept Broncos' $114.5 million offer by deadline |first=Mike|last=Klis|newspaper=USA TODAY|date=July 15, 2016|accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMiller finished the 2016 regular season with 13.5 sacks and 24 quarterback hits.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MillVo00.htm |title=Von Miller 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> In the last four games of the season, Miller did not record a sack, which was the longest such stretch in his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/page/Barnwellx170102/handing-nfl-awards-2016-comeback-player-year-mvp |title=Who should win NFL awards for 2016? Here's a guide |last=Barnwell |first=Bill |website=ESPN.com |access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref> He was named to his fifth career and third consecutive [[2017 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]], and his third First-team [[2016 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Three rookies, Matt Ryan among players named to All-Pro team|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000770458/article/three-rookies-matt-ryan-among-players-named-to-allpro-team?campaign=Twitter_atn|website=NFL.com|date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> and was ranked second by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]] as the highest ranked defensive player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://a.video.nfl.com/films/vodzilla/66114/170626_top100_no2_VonMiller-20170626_171425576_700k.mp4|title=NFL Top 100 Players hit or miss \ud83d\udcafof 2017 - No. 2 Von Miller|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n[[File:Von Miller 2017.jpg|thumb|Miller against the [[2017 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] in [[2017 Denver Broncos season|2017]]]]\nOn December 19, 2017, Miller was named to his sixth Pro Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> Miller was named the [[2018 Pro Bowl]] defensive MVP.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/01/28/von-miller-pro-bowl-defensive-mvp/ |title=Von Miller named Pro Bowl defensive MVP after win-sealing strip-sack |last=Jhabvala |first=Nicki |date=January 28, 2018 |work=The Denver Post |access-date=October 3, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In the 2017 season, he recorded his fourth consecutive season with at least ten sacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/MillVo00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Von Miller 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked ninth by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://broncoswire.usatoday.com/2018/06/26/denver-broncos-news-watch-von-miller-ranked-no-9-on-nfl-top-100-list/ |title=WATCH: Von Miller ranked No. 9 on NFL Top 100 list |date=2018-06-26 |website=Broncos Wire |language=en |access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nIn the Broncos' 2018 season opener against the [[2018 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Miller recorded three sacks and seven total tackles in the 27\u201324 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000960484/article/von-miller-wrecks-seahawks-on-threesack-day |title=Von Miller wrecks Seahawks on three-sack day |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=September 10, 2018 |work=NFL.com |access-date=October 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In Week 11, Miller intercepted [[Philip Rivers]] and returned it 42 yards to set up a touchdown, which helped ignite a 23-22 comeback win over the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]], earning him AFC Defensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000990812/article/samson-ebukam-barkley-among-players-of-the-week |title=Samson Ebukam, Saquon Barkley among Players of the Week |last=Knoblach |first=Austin |date=November 21, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2018 season, Miller recorded his 100th career sack (including postseason sacks), becoming the 5th-fastest player in NFL history to do so.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.timescall.com/ci_32290965/von-millers-sack-success-result-approach |title=Von Miller\u2019s sack success a result of approach |date=2018-11-24 |website=Longmont Times-Call |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/11/25/von-miller-sack-scientific-approach-broncos/ |title=Chase to 100: Von Miller\u2019s sack milestone result of \u201cscientific\u201d approach |date=2018-11-25 |website=The Denver Post |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-19}}</ref> He was also selected to the [[2019 Pro Bowl]] as a starting outside linebacker, which was his seventh career and fifth consecutive [[Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001001792/article/nfl-reveals-rosters-for-2019-pro-bowl-in-orlando |title=NFL reveals rosters for 2019 Pro Bowl in Orlando |date=December 18, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\n[[File:Henry and Miller.png|thumb|Miller alongside [[Derrick Henry]] at the [[2020 Pro Bowl]] ]]\nIn week 4 against the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], Miller sacked [[Gardner Minshew II]] twice in the 26-24 loss. Miller's second sack of the game was the 100th sack of his career. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128097 |title=Fournette leads Jags' 26-24 comeback over Broncos |date=29 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\nHe was also selected to the 2020 Pro Bowl as a starting outside linebacker, which was his eighth career and sixth consecutive Pro Bowl.\n\n==Franchise records==\nAs of the end of the [[2019 NFL season]], Miller has least five Denver Broncos franchise records for sacks, including:\n* Career (106.0)\n* Single season (18.5 in 2012)\n* Playoff career (6.5)\n* Single playoff season (5 in 2015)\n* Single playoff game (2.5 on both January 24, 2016 against the New England Patriots in the AFC Championship and February 7, 2016 against the Carolina Panthers in Super Bowl 50)\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===NFL statistics===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#9F9; width:3em;\"| \n|Career high\n|}\n====Regular season====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" float=\"left\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center; width:45%;\"\n|-\n|! colspan=\"15\" style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Denver Broncos|border=2}};\"|<div style=\"text-align:center;\">'''NFL career statistics'''</div>\n|-\n|! colspan=\"15\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Denver Broncos}};\"|<div style=\"text-align:center;\">'''Denver Broncos'''</div>\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Season\n!colspan=\"4\"|Tackling\n!colspan=\"4\"|Fumbles\n!colspan=\"4\"|Interceptions\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! GP !! GS !! Comb !! Solo !! Asst !! Sack !! FF !! FR !! Yds !! TD !! Int !! Yds !! TD !! PD\n|-\n| [[2011 Denver Broncos season|2011]] || 15 || 15 || 64 || 50 || 14 || 11.5|| 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || {{yes|4}} \n|-\n| [[2012 Denver Broncos season|2012]] || 16 || 16 || 68 || 55 || 13 || {{yes|18.5}} || {{yes|6}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || {{yes|1}} || 26 || {{yes|1}} || 2\n|-\n| [[2013 Denver Broncos season|2013]] || 9 || 9 || 34 || 27 || 7 || 5.0 || 3 || 1 || {{yes|60}} || {{yes|1}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| [[2014 Denver Broncos season|2014]] || 16 || 16 || 59 || 42 || 17 || 14.0 || 1 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n| [[2015 Denver Broncos season|2015]] || 16 || 16 || 35 || 30 || 5 || 11.0 || 4 || {{yes|3}} || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| [[2016 Denver Broncos season|2016]] || 16 || 16 || {{yes|78}} || {{yes|62}} || 16 || 13.5 || 3 || 0  || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| [[2017 Denver Broncos season|2017]] || 16 || 16 || 57 || 51 || 6 || 10.0 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| [[2018 Denver Broncos season|2018]] || 16 || 16 || 48 || 29 || {{yes|19}} || 14.5 || 4 || 2 || 0 || 0 || {{yes|1}} || {{yes|42}} || 0 || 3\n|-\n| [[2019 Denver Broncos season|2019]] || 15 ||15|| 46 || 33 || 13 || 8.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 2\n|-\n|-\n! Career || 135 || 135 || 489 || 379 || 110 || 106.0 || 25 || 8 |