.com/college-football/2016/2/8/10937696/von-miller-chicken-farmer-texas-am |title=Super Bowl MVP Von Miller is also a chicken farmer |website=SBNation.com |date=February 8, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2016|quote=\"Miller, a poultry science minor at Texas A&M, is actually a chicken farmer.\"}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Miller was arrested on a [[failure to appear]] warrant for driving-related charges in October 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/web/kmgh/sports/broncos/denver-broncos-linebacker-von-miller-arrested-on-outstanding-traffic-warrant|work=Thedenverchannel.com|title=Denver Broncos linebacker Von Miller arrested on outstanding traffic warrant at Centennial Gun Club|date=August 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016081856/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/web/kmgh/sports/broncos/denver-broncos-linebacker-von-miller-arrested-on-outstanding-traffic-warrant|archive-date=October 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Miller was cited for speeding and driving with a suspended license in [[Arapahoe County, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/broncos/2013/09/11/denver-broncos-von-miller-leagl-trouble-driving-without-license/2796865/ | work=USA Today | title=Von Miller cited for driving without license, speeding | date=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMiller was referenced in ''[[South Park]]'' during the [[South Park (season 20)|season 20]] episode \"[[Oh, Jeez]]\" when [[Gerald and Sheila Broflovski|Gerald Broflovski]] is sent to [[Denmark]] under the alias \"Ambassador Von Miller\"; this has been one of the show's numerous references to the Broncos, as many characters living in the series's titular town are fans of the team.\n\nIn April 2018, while on a guided fishing tour off the coast of Florida, Miller is alleged to have illegally landed a hammerhead shark. He is currently under investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/23028603/denver-broncos-lb-von-miller-being-investigated-shark-catch-coast-miami|title=Broncos LB Miller investigated for shark catch|work=ESPN.com|access-date=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\nVon Miller now has COVID-19\n=== Von's Vision ===\nIn 2012, Miller created Von's Vision to provide Denver-area youth with eye examinations and eyewear.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://vonmiller.org/\n| title = Von Miller {{!}} Von's Vision Foundation {{!}} A Prolanthropy-Managed Organization\n| website = vonmiller.org\n| access-date = March 1, 2016\n}}</ref> Von's Vision hosts Von's Vision Days throughout the year to provide children with free eye exams and glasses.<ref>{{Cite web\n| url = http://vonmiller.org/page.aspx?ID=1010\n| title = Von Miller {{!}} Von's Vision Foundation {{!}} A Prolanthropy-Managed Organization\n| website = vonmiller.org\n| access-date = March 1, 2016\n}}</ref>\n\nVon Miller's organization hosts two events for Denver-area children: Von's Vision Day and Von Miller's Back to School Vision Day. Von's Vision Day is a two-day program. The foundation partners with national and regional eyewear retailers to provide a citywide vision day for low-income Denver children. On the first day of the program, children receive free screenings, and if needed, free eye exams and an invitation to pick up their corrective eyewear at a later date. After the prescription glasses have been cut, Von hosts a Reveal Party where children are fitted for their glasses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kktv.com/sports/headlines/DENVER-BRONOCS-VON-MILLER-HOSTS-VONS-VISION-DAY--INVITES-200-UNDERPRIVELAGED-CHILDREN-IN-NEED-OF-EYE-SCREENING-250429741.html|title=DENVER BRONOCS\u2019 VON MILLER HOSTS VON\u2019S VISION DAY,  INVITES 200 UNDERPRIVELAGED CHILDREN IN NEED OF EYE SCREENING|last=PR|first=Broncos|website=www.kktv.com|access-date=March 9, 2016}}</ref> Children have the opportunity to interact with Von Miller and feel comfortable in their new glasses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vonmiller.org/page.aspx?ID=1010|title=Von Miller {{!}} Von's Vision Foundation {{!}} A Prolanthropy-Managed Organization|website=vonmiller.org|access-date=March 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nStarted in 2015, Von Miller hosts an annual vision day to serve children before they head back to school called Von Miller's Back to School Vision Day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://denver.cbslocal.com/2015/07/24/broncos-linebacker-von-miller-helps-kids-see-better/|title=Broncos Linebacker Von Miller Helps Kids See Better|access-date=March 9, 2016}}</ref> Every year 5,000 low-income 1st grade students enter the Denver Public School System without ever seeing an eye doctor. More than 1,900 of them need glasses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vonmiller.org/page.aspx?ID=1010|title=Von Miller {{!}} Von's Vision Foundation {{!}} A Prolanthropy-Managed Organization|website=www.vonmiller.org|access-date=March 9, 2016}}</ref> The program is designed to screen a child and, if needed, provide them with eyewear in a matter of minutes. Von Miller's Back to School Vision Day is designed to screen, write prescriptions, cut lenses and fit the glasses in under an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://prod.www.broncos.clubs.nfl.com/multimedia/videos/Vons-Vision-provides-glasses-to-school-kids/64f847f0-bbf3-4c76-9afe-69151da6eb52|title=Von's Vision provides glasses to school kids|website=prod.www.broncos.clubs.nfl.com|access-date=March 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310022231/http://prod.www.broncos.clubs.nfl.com/multimedia/videos/Vons-Vision-provides-glasses-to-school-kids/64f847f0-bbf3-4c76-9afe-69151da6eb52|archive-date=March 10, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===''Dancing with the Stars''===\nOn March 8, 2016, Miller was announced as one of the celebrities who would compete on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 22)|season 22]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. He was partnered with professional dancer [[Witney Carson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/dancing-stars-2016-season-22-celebrity-cast-revealed/story?id=37472389|title=\u2018Dancing With the Stars\u2019 2016: Season 22 Celebrity Cast Revealed Live on \u2018GMA\u2019|work=ABC News|date=March 8, 2016|accessdate=March 8, 2016}}</ref> On May 2, 2016, during a double elimination, Miller and Carson were eliminated and finished the competition in 8th place.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* {{Football stats |nfl=2495202 |espn=13976 |pfr=M/MillVo00}}\n* [https://www.denverbroncos.com/team/players-roster/von-miller/ Denver Broncos bio]\n* [https://12thman.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3111 Texas A&M Aggies bio]\n* [http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/von-miller?id=2495202 NFL combine profile]\n\n{{Denver Broncos roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes| title = Von Miller\u2014awards, championships, and honors| list1 = \n{{Dick Butkus Award (collegiate)}}\n{{2010 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2011 NFL Draft}}\n{{BroncosFirstPick}}\n{{Broncos2011DraftPicks}}\n{{AP Defensive Rookies of the Year}}\n{{Dick Butkus Award (professional)}}\n{{Super Bowl 50}}\n{{Super Bowl MVPs}}\n{{100 sacks club}}\n{{Walter Camp Alumni of the Year}}\n{{NFL2010s}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Von}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from DeSoto, Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football defensive ends]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M Aggies football players]]\n[[Category:Denver Broncos players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl MVPs]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football outside linebacker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Von Miller\n| image = Von Miller (Broncos).JPG\n| image_size = 200\n| alt =\n| caption = Miller with the Denver Broncos in 2011\n| current_team = Denver Broncos\n| position = [[Outside linebacker]]\n| number = 58\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1989|3|26|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dallas|Dallas, Texas]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lbs = 250\n| high_school = [[DeSoto High School (Texas)|DeSoto]] ([[DeSoto, Texas]])\n| college = [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]]\n| draftyear = 2011\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 2\n| pastteams =\n* [[Denver Broncos]] ({{NFL Year|2011}}\u2013present)\n| status = Active\n| highlights =\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl 50|50]])\n* [[Super Bowl MVP]]  ([[Super Bowl 50|50]])\n* 8\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2012 Pro Bowl|2011]], [[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]], [[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* 3\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2012 All-Pro Team|2012]], [[2015 All-Pro Team|2015]], [[2016 All-Pro Team|2016]])\n* 4\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2011 All-Pro Team|2011]], [[2014 All-Pro Team|2014]], [[2017 All-Pro Team|2017]], [[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]])\n* [[National Football League Rookie of the Year Award|NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year]] (2011)\n* [[Butkus Award|Butkus Award (pro)]] (2012)\n* [[National Football League 2010s All-Decade Team|NFL 2010s All-Decade Team]]\n* [[Butkus Award|Butkus Award (college)]] (2010)\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2009 College Football All-America Team|2009]], [[2010 College Football All-America Team|2010]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]] (2009, 2010)\n| statweek =\n| statseason = 2019\n| statlabel1 = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n| statvalue1 = 489\n| statlabel2 = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2 = 106.0\n| statlabel3 = [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n| statvalue3 = 25\n| statlabel4 = [[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n| statvalue4 = 9\n| statlabel5 = [[Pass deflections]]\n| statvalue5 = 21\n| statlabel6 = [[Interceptions]]\n| statvalue6 = 2\n| statlabel7 = [[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n| statvalue7 = 2\n| nfl-new = vonmiller/2495202\n}}\n\n'''Von B'Vsean Miller Jr.'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Augustyn|first=Adam|title=Von Miller|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Von-Miller|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.]]|website=Britannica.com|date=March 22, 2019|access-date=February 10, 2020}}</ref> (born March 26, 1989) is an [[American football]] [[outside linebacker]] for the [[Denver Broncos]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Miller played [[college football]] at [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]], where he earned consensus [[All-American]] honors and was awarded the [[Butkus Award]] as the most outstanding college linebacker in the nation. He was drafted by the Broncos second overall in the [[2011 NFL Draft]]. Considered among the best defenders in the league, he is an eight-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection, receiving first-team [[All-Pro]] honors as a rookie. At the conclusion of the [[2015 NFL season]], Miller was named [[Super Bowl MVP]] after the Broncos defeated the [[Carolina Panthers]] in [[Super Bowl 50]].  Following his Super Bowl victory, he appeared on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 22)|season 22]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n\n==High school career==\nMiller attended [[DeSoto High School (DeSoto, Texas)|DeSoto High School]] in [[DeSoto, Texas]], where he played for the DeSoto Eagles [[high school football]] team and ran track. In his junior year, he recorded 37 tackles, 14 tackles for loss, 7 sacks and 12 quarterback hurries. As a senior, he was named the District 8-5A Defensive MVP after making 76 tackles, 14 tackles for loss and 6 sacks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aggieathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/miller_von00.html |title=Player Bio: Von Miller |publisher=Texas A&M Official Athletic Site |accessdate=December 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20080910081644/http://www.aggieathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/miller_von00.html |archive-date=September 10, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He played with future Aggie teammate [[Cyrus Gray]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/vJsLgnF7EeCkhgAcxJSkrA/von-miller-cherishes-dallas-roots-heading-into-nfl-draft.htm |title=Von Miller cherishes Dallas roots heading into NFL Draft |last=Stephens |first=Mitch |website=MaxPreps.com |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[track & field]], Miller competed in events such as the [[110 metres hurdles|110m hurdles]] (PR of 14.38 s), [[triple jump]] (PR of 12.65 m), and [[javelin throw]] (PR of 37.24 m).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/von-miller-7501/|title=Von Miller|accessdate=February 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160222050010/https://www.trackingfootball.com/players/von-miller-7501/|archive-date=February 22, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nConsidered a four-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Miller was listed as the No. 15 weakside defensive end in the nation in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rivals.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Von-Miller-36463|title=Rivals|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>  He chose Texas A&M over offers from [[Florida Gators football|Florida]], [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] and [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]].\n\n==College career==\nMiller attended [[Texas A&M University]], where he played for the [[Texas A&M Aggies football]] team from 2007 to 2010.  As a freshman at [[defensive end]] in 2007, he was named Freshman All-[[Big 12]] by ''[[The Sporting News]]'' after posting 22 tackles, including 10 solo stops. He recorded two sacks, four tackles for loss, and a forced fumble.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/von-miller-1/gamelog/2007 |title=Von Miller 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> He played in a [[4-2-5 defense]]. He weighed 220 pounds during his freshman year.\n\nIn Spring 2008, newly hired head coach [[Mike Sherman]] was discouraged by Miller's habits of skipping class and failing to produce during practice. Sherman decided to suspend Miller for that spring. Disappointed, Miller considered transferring, but upon his father's insistence, stayed. Miller then adopted a more serious attitude.<ref name=SIapr2011>{{cite news|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2011/04/18/106057671/locked-out-and-loaded|title=Locked Out And Loaded | work=CNN | date=April 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104044347/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1184409/2/index.htm |archive-date=November 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAs a sophomore in 2008, Miller played at [[weakside linebacker]] under [[Joe Kines]]'s [[4\u20133 defense]]. He saw action in all 12 games, making 44 tackles, including 25 solo stops, and leading the team with 3.5 sacks. He made 7.5 tackles for loss, forced two fumbles, and recovered two more. His role was more confined to pass coverage, as opposed to rushing the quarterback, thus he wasn't able to showcase his pass-rushing abilities. In the final seven Big 12 games, he compiled just eight tackles.<ref name=FSSW31111>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsportssouthwest.com/03/11/11/Millers-return-to-Texas-AM-the-right-dec/landing_big12.html?blockID=438712&feedID=3742 |title=Miller's return to Texas A&M: the right decision |publisher=Fox Sports Southwest |date=March 11, 2011 |accessdate=March 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/von-miller-1/gamelog/2008 |title=Von Miller 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a junior in 2009, Miller adopted the role of the jack position, a defensive end/linebacker hybrid, which allowed him to utilize his pass rushing abilities. He enjoyed a breakout season for the Aggies, leading the nation in sacks with 17 and ranking fourth in the nation with 21 tackles for loss.<ref name=A2>{{cite news |first=Russ |last=Lande |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/feed/2010-09/draft-dish/story/draft-dish-nevada-qb-colin-kaepernick-moving-up-draft-boards |title=Draft Dish: Nevada QB Colin Kaepernick moving up draft boards |work=Sporting News |date=December 15, 2010 |accessdate=December 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211052546/http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/feed/2010-09/draft-dish/story/draft-dish-nevada-qb-colin-kaepernick-moving-up-draft-boards |archive-date=December 11, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For his efforts, Von Miller was named first team All Big-12 at [[defensive end]] and was named a first-team All-American by ''[[Sporting News]]'' and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/story/2009-12-15/2009-sporting-news-college-football-all-america-first-team|title=2009 Sporting News college football All-America first team}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/ncaa/12/15/all-america/index.html|title=SI.com's 2009 All-Americas | work=CNN | date=December 15, 2009}}</ref> He became the first Aggie to be named a first team All-American since [[Jason Webster]] in 1999.<ref name=AA82010>{{cite web |url=http://www.statesman.com/sports/aggies/will-aggies-make-it-von-miller-time-886643.html |title=Will Aggies make it Von Miller time? |publisher=Statesman.com |date=November 7, 2009 |accessdate=March 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120205554/http://www.statesman.com/sports/aggies/will-aggies-make-it-von-miller-time-886643.html |archive-date=November 20, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Then-Aggies defensive coordinator [[Joe Kines]] compared Miller to the late [[Derrick Thomas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Von-Miller-runs-a-449.html |title=Von Miller runs a 4.49 |publisher=National Football Post |date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=March 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311140237/http://www.nationalfootballpost.com/Von-Miller-runs-a-449.html |archive-date=March 11, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/von-miller-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Von Miller 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> Miller then studied and watched film of Thomas to familiarize himself with his game.\n\nAs a senior in 2010, Miller switched to playing as a [[3\u20134 defense|3\u20134 outside linebacker]] under [[Tim DeRuyter]]'s defense. Early in the season, Miller suffered a high ankle sprain that held him back for the first six games.<ref name=A2/> He posted 10.5 sacks and 17.5 tackles for loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/von-miller-1/gamelog/2010 |title=Von Miller 2010 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Herndon |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/01/its_von_millers_time_to_shine.html |title=It's Von Miller's time to shine at Senior Bowl |newspaper=Mobile Press-Register |date=January 28, 2011 |accessdate=March 11, 2011}}</ref> Again he made first-team All-Big 12 honors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&ATCLID=205038561&DB_OEM_ID=10410 |title=All-Big 12 Football Awards Announced \u2013 Big 12 Conference \u2013 Official Athletic Site |publisher=Big12sports.com |date=November 30, 2010 |accessdate=December 19, 2010}}</ref> and won the [[Butkus Award]] as the nation's top linebacker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aggiesports.com/football/120810-A-amp-amp-M-FOOTBALL |title=A&M's Von Miller wins Butkus Award |publisher=AggieSports.com |date=December 8, 2010 |accessdate=December 19, 2010}}</ref> He was also named a consensus first-team All-American.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncaafootball.fanhouse.com/2010/12/20/college-footballs-consensus-all-americans/ |title=College Football's 2010 Consensus All-Americans |publisher=NCAAfootball.fanhouse.com |date=December 20, 2010 |accessdate=March 11, 2011}}</ref> He received first team All-American honors from [[Walter Camp Football Foundation|Walter Camp]], [[Scout.com]], ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.profootballweekly.com/2010/12/21/pfws-2010-all-america-team |title=PFW's 2010 All-America team |magazine=Pro Football Weekly |date=December 21, 2010 |accessdate=March 11, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225091453/http://www.profootballweekly.com/2010/12/21/pfws-2010-all-america-team |archive-date=December 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[ESPN.com]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/feature/video/_/id/5948601/2010-all-american-team |title=ESPN.com's 2010 All-American Team |publisher=ESPN |date= |accessdate=March 11, 2011}}</ref> and the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/F/FBC_AP_ALL_AMERICA_LIST?SITE=FLPET&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT |title=AP All-America Team, List |work=St. Petersburg Times |date= |accessdate=December 19, 2010}}</ref> Miller graduated with a degree in poultry science and raises chickens in his spare time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsday.dallasnews.com/college-sports/sports/2013/05/02/von-miller-uses-texas-am-major-to-start-poultry-farm-at-dallas-home|title=Von Miller uses Texas A&M major to start poultry farm at Dallas home|date=May 2, 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Collegiate statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#500000; color:#ffffff;\" | Von Miller\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold;\" | Tackles\n! colspan=\"5\" styl